import static org.apache.kafka.common.record.internal.Records.LOG_OVERHEAD;

/**
 * Concrete {@link RecordBatch} implementation for magic version 2 and above (the current Kafka
 * record format). Instances wrap a read-only slice of a {@link java.nio.ByteBuffer} that holds the
 * complete, serialized representation of a single batch as it appears on the wire or on disk.
 *
 * <h2>Binary layout</h2>
 * <pre>{@code
 * RecordBatch =>
 *   BaseOffset            => Int64
 *   Length                => Int32
 *   PartitionLeaderEpoch  => Int32
 *   Magic                 => Int8
 *   CRC                   => Uint32
 *   Attributes            => Int16
 *   LastOffsetDelta       => Int32   // also serves as LastSequenceDelta
 *   BaseTimestamp         => Int64
 *   MaxTimestamp          => Int64
 *   ProducerId            => Int64
 *   ProducerEpoch         => Int16
 *   BaseSequence          => Int32
 *   RecordsCount          => Int32
 *   Records               => [Record]
 * }</pre>
 *
 * <p>When compression is enabled, the compressed record bytes are serialized directly after
 * the {@code RecordsCount} field. The CRC covers every byte from {@code Attributes} to the
 * end of the batch using the CRC-32C (Castagnoli) polynomial. The {@code PartitionLeaderEpoch}
 * field is intentionally excluded from the CRC to avoid recomputing it on every batch received
 * by the broker.
 *
 * <h2>Batch attributes (bits 0–6 of the {@code Attributes} field)</h2>
 * <pre>{@code
 * | Unused (7-15) | Delete Horizon Flag (6) | Control (5) | Transactional (4) | Timestamp Type (3) | Compression Type (0-2) |
 * }</pre>
 *
 * <h2>Compaction semantics</h2>
 * Unlike the older message formats, magic v2 preserves the first and last offset and sequence
 * numbers from the original batch through log compaction. This is necessary to correctly restore
 * idempotent producer state after a leader failure. If all records in a batch are removed during
 * compaction, the broker may retain an empty batch header (with {@code RecordsCount = 0}) to
 * preserve that producer sequence information. Empty batch headers are eventually removed once
 * the producer either writes a new sequence number or is expired due to inactivity.
 *
 * <h2>Timestamp semantics</h2>
 * <ul>
 *   <li>{@code BaseTimestamp} normally reflects the timestamp of the first record in the batch.
 *       For an empty batch it is set to {@link RecordBatch#NO_TIMESTAMP}. When the
 *       <em>delete horizon</em> flag is set, it holds the absolute wall-clock time at which
 *       tombstone records and aborted-transaction markers in this batch should be purged.</li>
 *   <li>{@code MaxTimestamp} holds the maximum timestamp across all current records when the
 *       timestamp type is {@link org.apache.kafka.common.record.TimestampType#CREATE_TIME}.
 *       For {@link org.apache.kafka.common.record.TimestampType#LOG_APPEND_TIME} it holds the
 *       broker-assigned append time, which is preserved after compaction.</li>
